[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] In numerical analysis, **Aitken's delta-squared process** or **Aitken extrapolation** is a series acceleration method used for accelerating the rate of convergence of a sequence.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] It is named after Alexander Aitken, who introduced this method in 1926 as part of an extension to Bernoulli's method.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] It is most useful for accelerating the convergence of a sequence that is converging linearly.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] A precursor form was known to Seki Kōwa (1642 – 1708) and applied to the rectification of the circle, i.e., to the calculation of π.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] with ${\textstyle \Delta x_{n}=x_{n+1}-x_{n}}$ and ${\textstyle \Delta ^{2}x_{n}=x_{n}-2x_{n+1}+x_{n+2}=\Delta x_{n+1}-\Delta x_{n}.}$ Both are the same sequence algebraically but the latter has improved numerical stability in computational implementation.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] ${\textstyle A[X]}$ is ill-defined if the sequence ${\textstyle \Delta ^{2}[X]=(\Delta ^{2}x_{n})}$ contains a zero element, which occurs if the sequence of forward differences, ${\textstyle \Delta [X]=(\Delta x_{n}),}$ has any repeated term.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] From a theoretical point of view, if that occurs only for a finite number of indices, one could apply the Aitken process to only the part of the sequence X with indices $n>n_{0}$ such that $n_{0}$ is the last index for which the sequence ${\textstyle \Delta [X]}$ repeats.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] Aitken's delta-squared process is an acceleration of convergence method and a particular case of a nonlinear sequence transformation.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] This means that asymptotically, the distance between the sequence and its limit shrinks by nearly the same proportion, $\mu ,$ on every step and the ratio of reduction becomes closer and closer to that proportion.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] The new process does not in general converge quadratically, but for an iterated function sequence satisfying $x_{n+1}=f(x_{n})$ for some function f converging to a fixed point, the accelerated sequence's convergence is quadratic.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] In this case, the technique is known as Steffensen's method.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] Empirically, the *A*-operation eliminates the "most important error term".
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] One can check this by considering a sequence of the form $x_{n}=\ell +a^{n}+b^{n}$ , where $0<b<a<1$ : The sequence $A[X]$ will then go to the limit ${\textstyle \ell }$ like $b^{n}$ goes to zero.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] One can also show that if a sequence X converges to its limit $\ell$ at a rate strictly greater than 1, $A[X]$ does not have a better rate of convergence.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] In practice, $A[X]$ often converges much faster to the limit than X does, as demonstrated by the example calculations below.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] Usually, it is much cheaper to calculate $A[X]$ (involving only calculation of differences, one multiplication and one division) than to calculate many more terms of the sequence X .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] Care must be taken, however, to avoid introducing errors due to insufficient precision when calculating the differences in the numerator and denominator of the expression.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] It is worth noting here that Aitken's method does not save the cost of calculating two iterations here; computation of the first three *${\textstyle A[X]}$* values required the first five ${\textstyle X}$ values.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] In this example, Aitken's method is applied to a sublinearly converging series and accelerates convergence considerably.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] The convergence is still sublinear, but much faster than the original convergence: the first ${\textstyle A[X]}$ value, whose computation required the first three ${\textstyle X}$ values, is closer to the limit than the eighth ${\textstyle X}$ value.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] The following is an example of using the Aitken extrapolation to help find the limit of the sequence $x_{n+1}=f(x_{n})$ when given some initial $x_{0},$ where the limit of this sequence is assumed to be a fixed point f (say $\alpha =f(\alpha )$ ).
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] This pseudo code also computes the Aitken approximation to $f^{\prime }(\alpha )$ .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] The Aitken extrapolates will be denoted by `aitkenX`.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] During the computation of the extrapolate, it is important to check if the denominator becomes too small, which could happen if we already have a large amount of accuracy; without this check, a large amount of error could be introduced by the division.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] This small number will be denoted by `epsilon`.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/aitken-s-delta-squared-process] Because the binary representation of the fixed point could be infinite (or at least too large to fit in the available memory), the calculation will stop once the approximation is within `tolerance` of the true value.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] In mathematics, **Anderson acceleration**, also called **Anderson mixing**, is a method for the acceleration of the convergence rate of fixed-point iterations.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] Anderson, this technique can be used to find the solution to fixed point equations $f(x)=x$ often arising in the field of computational science.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] Given a function $f:\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , consider the problem of finding a fixed point of f , which is a solution to the equation $f(x)=x$ .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] A classical approach to the problem is to employ a fixed-point iteration scheme; that is, given an initial guess $x_{0}$ for the solution, to compute the sequence $x_{k+1}=f(x_{k})$ until some convergence criterion is met.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] However, the convergence of such a scheme is not guaranteed in general; moreover, the rate of convergence is usually linear, which can become too slow if the evaluation of the function f is computationally expensive.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] Anderson acceleration is a method to accelerate the convergence of the fixed-point sequence.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] Define the residual $g(x)=f(x)-x$ , and denote $f_{k}=f(x_{k})$ and $g_{k}=g(x_{k})$ (where $x_{k}$ corresponds to the sequence of iterates from the previous paragraph).
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] Conventional stopping criteria can be used to end the iterations of the method.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] For example, iterations can be stopped when $\|x_{k+1}-x_{k}\|$ falls under a prescribed tolerance, or when the residual $g(x_{k})$ falls under a prescribed tolerance.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] With respect to the standard fixed-point iteration, the method has been found to converge faster and be more robust, and in some cases avoid the divergence of the fixed-point sequence.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] We can therefore rephrase the problem as an optimization problem where we want to minimize $\|g(x)\|_{2}$ .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] and our problem becomes to find the $\alpha$ that minimizes $\|G_{k}\alpha \|_{2}$ .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] After having found $\alpha _{k}$ , we could in principle calculate $x'_{k+1}$ .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] At each iteration of the algorithm, the constrained optimization problem $\operatorname {argmin} \|G_{k}\alpha \|_{2}$ , subject to $\alpha \in A_{k}$ needs to be solved.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] Solving the least-squares problem by solving the normal equations is generally not advisable due to potential numerical instabilities and generally high computational cost.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] Stagnation in the method (i.e. subsequent iterations with the same value, $x_{k+1}=x_{k}$ ) causes the method to break down, due to the singularity of the least-squares problem.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] Similarly, near-stagnation ( $x_{k+1}\approx x_{k}$ ) results in bad conditioning of the least squares problem.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] Moreover, the choice of the parameter m might be relevant in determining the conditioning of the least-squares problem, as discussed below.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] The algorithm can be modified introducing a variable relaxation parameter (or mixing parameter) $\beta _{k}>0$ .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] The parameter m determines how much information from previous iterations is used to compute the new iteration $x_{k+1}$ .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] On the one hand, if m is chosen to be too small, too little information is used and convergence may be undesirably slow.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] On the other hand, if m is too large, information from old iterations may be retained for too many subsequent iterations, so that again convergence may be slow.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] Moreover, the choice of m affects the size of the optimization problem.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] A too large value of m may worsen the conditioning of the least squares problem and the cost of its solution.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] In general, the particular problem to be solved determines the best choice of the m parameter.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] With respect to the algorithm described above, the choice of $m_{k}$ at each iteration can be modified.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] One possibility is to choose $m_{k}=k$ for each iteration k (sometimes referred to as Anderson acceleration without truncation).
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] This way, every new iteration $x_{k+1}$ is computed using all the previously computed iterations.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] A more sophisticated technique is based on choosing $m_{k}$ so as to maintain a small enough conditioning for the least-squares problem.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] Newton's method can be applied to the solution of $f(x)-x=0$ to compute a fixed point of $f(x)$ with quadratic convergence.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] However, such method requires the evaluation of the exact derivative of $f(x)$ , which can be very costly.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] Approximating the derivative by means of finite differences is a possible alternative, but it requires multiple evaluations of $f(x)$ at each iteration, which again can become very costly.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] Anderson acceleration requires only one evaluation of the function $f(x)$ per iteration, and no evaluation of its derivative.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] On the other hand, the convergence of an Anderson-accelerated fixed point sequence is still linear in general.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] Several authors have pointed out similarities between the Anderson acceleration scheme and other methods for the solution of non-linear equations.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] Moreover, several equivalent or nearly equivalent methods have been independently developed by other authors, although most often in the context of some specific application of interest rather than as a general method for fixed point equations.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/anderson-acceleration] The following is an example implementation in MATLAB language of the Anderson acceleration scheme for finding the fixed-point of the function $f(x)=\sin(x)+\arctan(x)$ .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] It can be understood as an abstract formulation of Picard's method of successive approximations.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] The theorem is named after Stefan Banach (1892–1945) who first stated it in 1922.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] The value q is called a *Lipschitz constant* for T , and a minimal such q is sometimes called "the best Lipschitz constant" of T .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] This follows by induction on n , using the fact that T is a contraction mapping.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] Then we can show that $(x_{n})_{n\in \mathbb {N} }$ is a Cauchy sequence.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] This proves that the sequence $(x_{n})_{n\in \mathbb {N} }$ is Cauchy.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] As a contraction mapping, T is continuous, so bringing the limit inside T was justified.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] where the equality is due to $p_{1},p_{2}$ being fixed points of T , the first inequality is due to T being a contraction mapping, and the last inequality is due to $q<1$ and $d(p_{1},p_{2})>0$ as $p_{1}\neq p_{2}$ .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] Several converses of the Banach contraction principle exist.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] Let $f:X\rightarrow X$ be a map of an abstract set such that each iterate $f^{n}$ has a unique fixed point.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] Let $q\in (0,1)$ , then there exists a complete metric on X such that f is contractive, and q is the contraction constant.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] Indeed, very weak assumptions suffice to obtain such a kind of converse.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] In this case the metric is in fact an ultrametric.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] There are a number of generalizations (some of which are immediate corollaries).
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] Let $T:X\rightarrow X$ be a map on a complete non-empty metric space.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] In applications, the existence and uniqueness of a fixed point often can be shown directly with the standard Banach fixed point theorem, by a suitable choice of the metric that makes the map T a contraction.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] Indeed, the above result by Bessaga strongly suggests to look for such a metric.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] See also the article on fixed point theorems in infinite-dimensional spaces for generalizations.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] In a non-empty compact metric space, any function T satisfying $d(T(x),T(y))<d(x,y)$ for all distinct $x,y$ , has a unique fixed point.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] The proof is simpler than the Banach theorem, because the function $d(T(x),x)$ is continuous, and therefore assumes a minimum, which is easily shown to be zero.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] A different class of generalizations arise from suitable generalizations of the notion of metric space, e.g. by weakening the defining axioms for the notion of metric.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] Some of these have applications, e.g., in the theory of programming semantics in theoretical computer science.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] An application of the Banach fixed-point theorem and fixed-point iteration can be used to quickly obtain an approximation of $\pi$ with high accuracy.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] Consider the function $f(x)=x+\sin(x)$ .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] It can be verified that $\pi$ is a fixed point of f , and that f maps the interval $\left[{\frac {3\pi }{4}},{\frac {5\pi }{4}}\right]$ to itself.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] Therefore, by an application of the mean value theorem, f has a Lipschitz constant less than 1 (namely $1-1/{\sqrt {2}}$ ).
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] Applying the Banach fixed-point theorem shows that the fixed point $\pi$ is the unique fixed point on the interval, allowing for fixed-point iteration to be used.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/banach-fixed-point-theorem] For example, the value 3 may be chosen to start the fixed-point iteration, as ${\frac {3\pi }{4}}\leqslant 3\leqslant {\frac {5\pi }{4}}$ .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] Among hundreds of fixed-point theorems, Brouwer's is particularly well known, due in part to its use across numerous fields of mathematics.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] In its original field, this result is one of the key theorems characterizing the topology of Euclidean spaces, along with the Jordan curve theorem, the hairy ball theorem, the invariance of dimension and the Borsuk–Ulam theorem.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] This gives it a place among the fundamental theorems of topology.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The theorem is also used for proving deep results about differential equations and is covered in most introductory courses on differential geometry.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] It appears in unlikely fields such as game theory.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] In economics, Brouwer's fixed-point theorem and its extension, the Kakutani fixed-point theorem, play a central role in the proof of existence of general equilibrium in market economies as developed in the 1950s by economics Nobel prize winners Kenneth Arrow and Gérard Debreu.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The theorem was first studied in view of work on differential equations by the French mathematicians around Henri Poincaré and Charles Émile Picard.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] Proving results such as the Poincaré–Bendixson theorem requires the use of topological methods.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] This work at the end of the 19th century opened into several successive versions of the theorem.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The case of differentiable mappings of the *n*-dimensional closed ball was first proved in 1910 by Jacques Hadamard and the general case for continuous mappings by Brouwer in 1911.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The theorem has several formulations, depending on the context in which it is used and its degree of generalization.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The theorem holds only for functions that are *endomorphisms* (functions that have the same set as the domain and codomain) and for nonempty sets that are *compact* (thus, in particular, bounded and closed) and *convex* (or homeomorphic to convex).
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The following examples show why the pre-conditions are important.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] which is a continuous function from $\mathbb {R}$ to itself.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] As it shifts every point to the right, it cannot have a fixed point.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The space $\mathbb {R}$ is convex and closed, but not bounded.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] which is a continuous function from the open interval $(-1,1)$ to itself.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] Since the point $x=1$ is not part of the interval, there is no point in the domain such that $f(x)=x$ .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The set $(-1,1)$ is convex and bounded, but not closed.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] On the other hand, the function f does have a fixed point in the *closed* interval $[-1,1]$ , namely $x=1$ .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The closed interval $[-1,1]$ is compact, the open interval $(-1,1)$ is not.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] Convexity is not strictly necessary for Brouwer's fixed-point theorem.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] Because the properties involved (continuity, being a fixed point) are invariant under homeomorphisms, Brouwer's fixed-point theorem is equivalent to forms in which the domain is required to be a closed unit ball $D^{n}$ .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] For the same reason it holds for every set that is homeomorphic to a closed ball (and therefore also closed, bounded, connected, without holes, etc.).
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The following example shows that Brouwer's fixed-point theorem does not work for domains with holes.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] Consider the function $f(x)=-x$ , which is a continuous function from the unit circle to itself.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] Since $-x\neq x$ holds for any point of the unit circle, f has no fixed point.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The analogous example works for the n -dimensional sphere (or any symmetric domain that does not contain the origin).
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The unit circle is closed and bounded, but it has a hole (and so it is not convex).
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] The function f *does* have a fixed point for the unit disc, since it takes the origin to itself.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/brouwer-fixed-point-theorem] A formal generalization of Brouwer's fixed-point theorem for "hole-free" domains can be derived from the Lefschetz fixed-point theorem.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/contraction-mapping] $d(f(x),f(y))\leq k\,d(x,y).$ The smallest such value of *k* is called the **Lipschitz constant** of *f*.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/contraction-mapping] Contractive maps are sometimes called **Lipschitzian maps**.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/contraction-mapping] If the above condition is instead satisfied for *k* ≤ 1, then the mapping is said to be a non-expansive map.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/contraction-mapping] More generally, the idea of a contractive mapping can be defined for maps between metric spaces.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/contraction-mapping] Thus, if (*M*, *d*) and (*N*, *d'*) are two metric spaces, then $f:M\rightarrow N$ is a contractive mapping if there is a constant $0\leq k<1$ such that $d'(f(x),f(y))\leq k\,d(x,y)$ for all *x* and *y* in *M*.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/contraction-mapping] Every contraction mapping is Lipschitz continuous and hence uniformly continuous (for a Lipschitz continuous function, the constant *k* is no longer necessarily less than 1).
[src:fixed-point-iteration/contraction-mapping] A contraction mapping has at most one fixed point.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/contraction-mapping] Moreover, the Banach fixed-point theorem states that every contraction mapping on a non-empty complete metric space has a unique fixed point, and that for any *x* in *M* the iterated function sequence *x*, *f* (*x*), *f* (*f* (*x*)), *f* (*f* (*f* (*x*))), ... converges to the fixed point.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/contraction-mapping] This concept is very useful for iterated function systems where contraction mappings are often used.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/contraction-mapping] Banach's fixed-point theorem is also applied in proving the existence of solutions of ordinary differential equations, and is used in one proof of the inverse function theorem.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/contraction-mapping] Contraction mappings play an important role in dynamic programming problems.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/contraction-mapping] A firmly non-expansive mapping is always non-expansive, via the Cauchy–Schwarz inequality.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/contraction-mapping] The class of firmly non-expansive maps is closed under convex combinations, but not compositions.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/contraction-mapping] This class includes proximal mappings of proper, convex, lower-semicontinuous functions, hence it also includes orthogonal projections onto non-empty closed convex sets.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/contraction-mapping] The class of firmly nonexpansive operators is equal to the set of resolvents of maximally monotone operators.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/contraction-mapping] Surprisingly, while iterating non-expansive maps has no guarantee to find a fixed point (e.g. multiplication by -1), firm non-expansiveness is sufficient to guarantee global convergence to a fixed point, provided a fixed point exists.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/contraction-mapping] More precisely, if $\operatorname {Fix} f:=\{x\in {\mathcal {H}}\ |\ f(x)=x\}\neq \varnothing ,$ then for any initial point $x_{0}\in {\mathcal {H}}$ , iterating $x_{n+1}=f(x_{n}),\quad \forall n\in \mathbb {N}$ yields convergence to a fixed point $x_{n}\to z\in \operatorname {Fix} f$ .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/contraction-mapping] This convergence might be weak in an infinite-dimensional setting.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/contraction-mapping] A **subcontraction map** or **subcontractor** is a map *f* on a metric space (*M*, *d*) such that $d(f(x),f(y))\leq d(x,y);$ $d(f(f(x)),f(x))<d(f(x),x)\quad {\text{unless}}\quad x=f(x).$ If the image of a subcontractor *f* is compact, then *f* has a fixed point.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/contraction-mapping] In a locally convex space (*E*, *P*) with topology given by a set *P* of seminorms, one can define for any *p* ∈ *P* a *p*-contraction as a map *f* such that there is some *k**p* < 1 such that *p*(*f*(*x*) − *f*(*y*)) ≤ *kp p*(*x* − *y*).
[src:fixed-point-iteration/contraction-mapping] If *f* is a *p*-contraction for all *p* ∈ *P* and (*E*, *P*) is sequentially complete, then *f* has a fixed point, given as limit of any sequence *x**n*+1 = *f*(*x**n*), and if (*E*, *P*) is Hausdorff, then the fixed point is unique.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] In numerical analysis, **fixed-point iteration** is a method of computing fixed points of a function.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] More generally, the function f can be defined on any metric space with values in that same space.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] An *attracting fixed point* of a function *f* is a fixed point *x*fix of *f* with a neighborhood *U* of "close enough" points around *x*fix such that for any value of x in *U*, the fixed-point iteration sequence $x,\ f(x),\ f(f(x)),\ f(f(f(x))),\dots$ is contained in *U* and converges to *x*fix.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] The basin of attraction of *x*fix is the largest such neighborhood *U*.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] The natural cosine function ("natural" means in radians, not degrees or other units) has exactly one fixed point, and that fixed point is attracting.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] In this case, "close enough" is not a stringent criterion at all—to demonstrate this, start with *any* real number and repeatedly press the *cos* key on a calculator (checking first that the calculator is in "radians" mode).
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] It eventually converges to the Dottie number (about 0.739085133), which is a fixed point.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] That is where the graph of the cosine function intersects the line $y=x$ .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] For example, 0 is a fixed point of the function *f*(*x*) = 2*x*, but iteration of this function for any value other than zero rapidly diverges.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] We say that the fixed point of $f(x)=2x$ is repelling.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] An attracting fixed point is said to be a *stable fixed point* if it is also Lyapunov stable.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] A fixed point is said to be a *neutrally stable fixed point* if it is Lyapunov stable but not attracting.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] The center of a linear homogeneous differential equation of the second order is an example of a neutrally stable fixed point.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] Multiple attracting points can be collected in an *attracting fixed set*.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] The Banach fixed-point theorem gives a sufficient condition for the existence of attracting fixed points.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] A contraction mapping function f defined on a complete metric space has precisely one fixed point, and the fixed-point iteration is attracted towards that fixed point for any initial guess $x_{0}$ in the domain of the function.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] Common special cases are that (1) f is defined on the real line with real values and is Lipschitz continuous with Lipschitz constant $L<1$ , and (2) the function *f* is continuously differentiable in an open neighbourhood of a fixed point *x*fix, and $|f'(x_{\text{fix}})|<1$ .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] Although there are other fixed-point theorems, this one in particular is very useful because not all fixed-points are attractive.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] When constructing a fixed-point iteration, it is very important to make sure it converges to the fixed point.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] We can usually use the Banach fixed-point theorem to show that the fixed point is attractive.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] Attracting fixed points are a special case of a wider mathematical concept of attractors.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] Fixed-point iterations are a discrete dynamical system on one variable.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] Bifurcation theory studies dynamical systems and classifies various behaviors such as attracting fixed points, periodic orbits, or strange attractors.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] In computational mathematics, an iterative method is a mathematical procedure that uses an initial value to generate a sequence of improving approximate solutions for a class of problems, in which the n-th approximation is derived from the previous ones.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] Convergent fixed-point iterations are mathematically rigorous formalizations of iterative methods.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] The speed of convergence of the iteration sequence can be increased by using a convergence acceleration method such as Anderson acceleration and Aitken's delta-squared process.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] The application of Aitken's method to fixed-point iteration is known as Steffensen's method, and it can be shown that Steffensen's method yields a rate of convergence that is at least quadratic.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] The term *chaos game* refers to a method of generating the fixed point of any iterated function system (IFS).
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] Starting with any point *x*0, successive iterations are formed as *x**k*+1 = *f**r*(*x**k*), where *f**r* is a member of the given IFS randomly selected for each iteration.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] Hence the chaos game is a randomized fixed-point iteration.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] The chaos game allows plotting the general shape of a fractal such as the Sierpinski triangle by repeating the iterative process a large number of times.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] More mathematically, the iterations converge to the fixed point of the IFS.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/fixed-point-iteration] Whenever *x*0 belongs to the attractor of the IFS, all iterations *x**k* stay inside the attractor and, with probability 1, form a dense set in the latter.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/kantorovich-theorem] The **Kantorovich theorem**, or Newton–Kantorovich theorem, is a mathematical statement on the semi-local convergence of Newton's method.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/kantorovich-theorem] It was first stated by Leonid Kantorovich in 1948.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/kantorovich-theorem] It is similar to the form of the Banach fixed-point theorem, although it states existence and uniqueness of a zero rather than a fixed point.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/kantorovich-theorem] Newton's method constructs a sequence of points that under certain conditions will converge to a solution x of an equation $f(x)=0$ or a vector solution of a system of equation $F(x)=0$ .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/kantorovich-theorem] The Kantorovich theorem gives conditions on the initial point of this sequence.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/kantorovich-theorem] If those conditions are satisfied then a solution exists close to the initial point and the sequence converges to that point.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/kantorovich-theorem] Let $X\subset \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ be an open subset and $F:X\subset \mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ a differentiable function with a Jacobian $F^{\prime }(\mathbf {x} )$ that is locally Lipschitz continuous (for instance if F is twice differentiable).
[src:fixed-point-iteration/kantorovich-theorem] The norm on the left is the operator norm.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/kantorovich-theorem] Now choose any initial point $\mathbf {x} _{0}\in X$ .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/kantorovich-theorem] The next assumption is that not only the next point $\mathbf {x} _{1}=\mathbf {x} _{0}+\mathbf {h} _{0}$ but the entire ball $B(\mathbf {x} _{1},\|\mathbf {h} _{0}\|)$ is contained inside the set X .
[src:fixed-point-iteration/kantorovich-theorem] Let M be the Lipschitz constant for the Jacobian over this ball (assuming it exists).
[src:fixed-point-iteration/kantorovich-theorem] 2. the Newton iteration starting in $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ converges to $\mathbf {x} ^{*}$ with at least linear order of convergence.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/kantorovich-theorem] In 1986, Yamamoto proved that the error evaluations of the Newton method such as Doring (1969), Ostrowski (1971, 1973), Gragg-Tapia (1974), Potra-Ptak (1980), Miel (1981), Potra (1984), can be derived from the Kantorovich theorem.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/kantorovich-theorem] There is a *q*-analog for the Kantorovich theorem.
[src:fixed-point-iteration/kantorovich-theorem] For other generalizations/variations, see Ortega & Rheinboldt (1970).
[src:fixed-point-iteration/kantorovich-theorem] Oishi and Tanabe claimed that the Kantorovich theorem can be applied to obtain reliable solutions of linear programming.
